08306nam a22010335i 9780812209990DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20142014pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)890184186  a97808122099907 a10.9783/97808122099902doi  a(DE-B1597)450994  a(OCoLC)888552457  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aK5181b.A238 2014 7aPOL0350102bisacsh04a342.08/422300aAbortion Law in Transnational Perspective :bCases and Controversies /ced. by Bernard M. Dickens, Joanna N. Erdman, Rebecca J. Cook. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (480 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aPennsylvania Studies in Human Rights00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tPart I. Constitutional Values and Regulatory Regimes -- t1. The Constitutionalization of Abortion -- t2. Abortion in Portugal: New Trends in European Constitutionalism -- t3. Women’s Rights in the Abortion Decision of the Slovak Constitutional Court -- t4. Proportionality in the Constitutional Review of Abortion Law -- t5. A Functionalist Approach to Comparative Abortion Law119 -- tPart II. Procedural Justice and Liberal Access -- t6. The Procedural Turn: Abortion at the European Court of Human Rights -- t7. The Struggle Against Informal Rules on Abortion in Argentina -- t8. Reforming African Abortion Laws and Practice: The Place of Transparency -- tPart III. Framing and Claiming Rights -- t9. The Medical Framework and Early Medical Abortion in the U.K.: How Can a State Control Swallowing? -- t10. The Right to Conscience -- t11. Catholic Constitutionalism on Sex, Women, and the Beginning of Life -- t12. Bringing Abortion into the Brazilian Public Debate: Legal Strategies for Anencephalic Pregnancy -- t13. Toward Transformative Equality in Nepal: The Lakshmi Dhikta Decision -- tPart IV. Narratives and Social Meaning -- t14. Reckoning with Narratives of Innocent Suffering in Transnational Abortion Litigation -- t15. Narratives of Prenatal Personhood in Abortion Law -- t16. Stigmatized Meanings of Criminal Abortion Law -- tTable of Cases -- tTable of Legislation, Treaties, and Other Relevant Instruments -- tNotes -- tContributors -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIt is increasingly implausible to speak of a purely domestic abortion law, as the legal debates around the world draw on precedents and influences of different national and regional contexts. While the United States and Western Europe may have been the vanguard of abortion law reform in the latter half of the twentieth century, Central and South America are proving to be laboratories of thought and innovation in the twenty-first century, as are particular countries in Africa and Asia. Abortion Law in Transnational Perspective offers a fresh look at significant transnational legal developments in recent years, examining key judicial decisions, constitutional texts, and regulatory reforms of abortion law in order to envision ways ahead.The chapters investigate issues of access, rights, and justice, as well as social constructions of women, sexuality, and pregnancy, through different legal procedures and regimes. They address the promises and risks of using legal procedure to achieve reproductive justice from different national, regional, and international vantage points; how public and courtroom debates are framed within medical, religious, and human rights arguments; the meaning of different narratives that recur in abortion litigation and language; and how respect for women and prenatal life is expressed in various legal regimes. By exploring how legal actors advocate, regulate, and adjudicate the issue of abortion, this timely volume seeks to build on existing developments to bring about change of a larger order.Contributors: Luis Roberto Barroso, Paola Bergallo, Rebecca J. Cook, Bernard M. Dickens, Joanna N. Erdman, Lisa M. Kelly, Adriana Lamačková, Julieta Lemaitre, Alejandro Madrazo, Charles G. Ngwena, Rachel Rebouché, Ruth Rubio-Marín, Sally Sheldon, Reva B. Siegel, Verónica Undurraga, Melissa Upreti.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aAbortionxLaw and legislation. 4aHuman Rights. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Human Rights.2bisacsh  aHuman Rights.  aLaw.  aPublic Policy.1 aBarroso, Luís Roberto, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBergallo, Paola, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCook, Rebecca J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCook, Rebecca J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDickens, Bernard M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDickens, Bernard M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aErdman, Joanna N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErdman, Joanna N., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKelly, Lisa M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLamačková, Adriana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLemaitre, Julieta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMadrazo, Alejandro, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNgwena, Charles G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRebouché, Rachel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRubio-Marín, Ruth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSheldon, Sally, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSiegel, Reva B., econtributor.